    "# 02 - Variogram Models"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "subslide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "This tutorial will guide you through the theoretical variogram models available for the `Variogram` class. \n",
    "\n",
    "**In this tutorial you will learn:**\n",
    "\n",
    "* how to choose an appropiate model function\n",
    "* how to judge fitting quality\n",
    "* about sample size influence"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "skip"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from skgstat import Variogram, OrdinaryKriging\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "plt.style.use('ggplot')"
   ]
  },

    "## 2.1 Load data"
   ]
  },

    }
   },
   "source": [
    "There are three prepared data sets in the `./data` folder. Each of them is a generated random field with different underlying spatial properties. We will use only the first one, but you can re-run all the examples with any of the other fields."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "skip"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "data1 = pd.read_csv('data/sample_matern_15.csv')\n",
    "data2 = pd.read_csv('data/sample_matern_40.csv')\n",
    "data3 = pd.read_csv('data/sample_spherical_noise.csv')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "skip"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def plot_scatter(data, ax):\n",
    "    art = ax.scatter(data.x, data.y, 50, c=data.z, cmap='plasma')\n",
    "    plt.colorbar(art, ax=ax)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {
    "scrolled": true,
    "slideshow": {

   "source": [
    "## 2.2 Comparing theoretical models"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "skip"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "One of the features of `scikit-gstat` is the fact that it is programmed object oriented. That means, we can just instantiate a `Variogram` object and start changing arguments unitl it models spatial dependency in our observations well."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "subslide"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 576x360 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "V1 = Variogram(data1[['x', 'y']].values, data1.z.values, normalize=False)\n",
    "V1.plot(show=False);"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "skip"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "The data set includes 200 observations, consequently we can increase the number of lag classes. Additionally, the histogram shows, that the lags over 100 units are backed up by just a few observations. Thus, we can limit the lag classes to at least 100."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "subslide"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 576x360 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "V1.maxlag = 100\n",
    "V1.n_lags = 25\n",
    "V1.plot(show=False);"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "subslide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "That's not too bad. Now, we can try different theoretical models. It is always a good idea to judge the fit visually, Especially, because we want it to fit to close bins more accurately than to distant bins, as they will ultimately determine the Kriging weights. \n",
    "Nevertheless, `Variogram` has a `rmse` and a `r2` property, that can be used as a quality measure for the fit.\n",
    "The `Variogram.plot` function also accepts one or two matplotlib subplot axes to plot the lag classes histogram and variogram plot into them. The histogram can also be turned off."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "subslide"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "e:\\dropbox\\python\\scikit-gstat\\skgstat\\models.py:17: RuntimeWarning: invalid value encountered in double_scalars\n",
      "  return func(*args, **kwargs)\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1296x720 with 6 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, _a = plt.subplots(2,3, figsize=(18, 10), sharex=True, sharey=True)\n",
    "axes = _a.flatten()\n",
    "for i, model in enumerate(('spherical', 'exponential', 'gaussian', 'matern', 'stable', 'cubic')):\n",
    "    V1.model = model\n",
    "    V1.plot(axes=axes[i], hist=False, show=False)\n",
    "    axes[i].set_title('Model: %s; RMSE: %.2f' % (model, V1.rmse))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "skip"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "This is quite important. We find all 6 models to describe the experimental variogram equally well in terms of RMSE.\n",
    "However, the `cubic` and `gaussian` model are off the experimental values almost all the time. On short distances, the model is underestimating and on medium distances (up to the effective range) it is overestimating. The `exponential` model is overestimating all the time. The `spherical`, `matern` and `stable` model seem to be pretty good on short distances.\n",
    "\n",
    "But what does this difference look like, when it comes to interpolation?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "skip"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def interpolate(V, ax):\n",
    "    xx, yy = np.mgrid[0:99:100j, 0:99:100j]\n",
    "    ok = OrdinaryKriging(V, min_points=5, max_points=15, mode='exact')\n",
    "    field = ok.transform(xx.flatten(), yy.flatten()).reshape(xx.shape)\n",
    "    art = ax.matshow(field, origin='lower', cmap='plasma')\n",
    "    ax.set_title('%s model' % V.model.__name__)\n",
    "    plt.colorbar(art, ax=ax)\n",
    "    return field"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {
    "scrolled": false,
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "subslide"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [

     ]

    "While most of the results look fairly similar there are a few things to notice:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Gaussian model is far off, producing estimations far outside the observed value ranges\n",
    "2. All other models produce quite comparable numbers\n",
    "3. The Matérn model fails, when recalculating the observations themselves\n",
    "\n",
    "You have to remind that we had quite some observations. How does that look like, when the number of observations is decreased?"
   ]

   "source": [
    "We decreased the number of observations so far, that the `max_points` attribute came into effect. In the other cases the Kriging interpolator found so many close observations, that limiting them to 15 had the effect, that estimations were usually derived from obserations within a few units. Now, even if enough points are within the range, we use observations from medium distances. Here, the different shapes of the models come into effect, as could be seen from the last example. "
